# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emacs-lisp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp code is used to modify, extend and customize Emacs.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Those not wanting to write the code themselves can use the Customize function instead.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] It provides a set of preferences pages allowing the user to set options and preview their effect in the running Emacs session.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] When the user saves their changes, Customize simply writes the necessary Emacs Lisp code to the user's config file, which can be set to a special file that only Customize uses, to avoid the possibility of altering the user's own file.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Besides being a programming language that can be compiled to bytecode and to machine code, Emacs Lisp can also function as an interpreted scripting language, much like the Unix Bourne shell or Perl, by calling Emacs in *batch mode*.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In this way it may be called from the command line or via an executable file, and its editing functions, such as buffers and movement commands are available to the program just as in the normal mode.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] No user interface is presented when Emacs is started in batch mode; it simply executes the passed-in script and exits, displaying any output from the script.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp is also termed **Elisp**, although there are also older, unrelated Lisp dialects with that name.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp is most closely related to Maclisp, with some later influence from Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] It supports imperative and functional programming methods.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Lisp was the default extension language for Emacs derivatives such as EINE and ZWEI.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] When Richard Stallman forked Gosling Emacs into GNU Emacs, he also chose Lisp as the extension language, because of its powerful features, including the ability to treat functions as data.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The Lisp dialect used in Emacs differs substantially from the more modern Common Lisp and Scheme dialects used for applications programming.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] A prominent characteristic of Emacs Lisp is in its use of dynamic rather than lexical scope by default.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] That is, a function may reference local variables in the scope it is called from, but not in the scope where it was defined.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Recently, there has been an ongoing effort to update code to use lexical scoping, for reasons outlined below.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The development of Emacs Lisp was guided by the goal of providing data structures and features specific to making a versatile text editor over implementing a general-purpose programming language.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] For example, Emacs Lisp cannot easily read a file a line at a time—the entire file must be read into an Emacs buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] However, Emacs Lisp provides many features for navigating and modifying buffer text at a sentence, paragraph, or higher syntactic level as defined by modes.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Here follows a simple example of an Emacs extension written in Emacs Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In Emacs, the editing area can be split into separate areas called *windows*, each displaying a different *buffer*.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] A buffer is a region of text loaded into Emacs' memory (possibly from a file) which can be saved into a text document.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Users can press the default C-x 2 key binding to open a new window.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] This runs the Emacs Lisp function `split-window-below`.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Normally, when the new window appears, it displays the same buffer as the previous one.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Suppose we wish to make it display the next available buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The first statement, `(defun ...)`, defines a new function, `my-split-window-func`, which calls `split-window-below` (the old window-splitting function), then tells the new window to display another (new) buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The second statement, `(global-set-key ...)` re-binds the key sequence "C-x 2" to the new function.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] This can also be written using the feature named *advice*, which allows a user to create wrappers around extant functions instead of defining their own.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] This has the advantages of not needing keybindings to be changed, of working wherever the original function is called, and of being simpler to write, but the disadvantage of making debugging more complex.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] This instructs `split-window-below` to execute the user-supplied code whenever it is called, after executing the rest of the function.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Advice can also be specified to execute before the original function, around it (literally wrapping the original), or to conditionally execute the original function based on the results of the advice.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs 24.4 replaces this `defadvice` mechanism with `advice-add`, which is claimed to be more flexible and simpler.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] These changes take effect as soon as the code is evaluated.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] It is not necessary to recompile, restart Emacs, or even rehash a configuration file.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] If the code is saved into an Emacs init file, then Emacs will load the extension the next time it starts.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Otherwise, the changes must be reevaluated manually when Emacs is restarted.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp source code is stored in filesystems as plain text files, by convention with the filename suffix "`.el`".
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The user's init file is an exception, often appearing as "`.emacs`" despite being evaluated as any Emacs Lisp code.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Since the mid-1990s, Emacs also loads `~/.emacs.el` and `~/.emacs.d/init.el`.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Further, users may specify any file to load as a config file on the command line, or explicitly state that no config file is to be loaded.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] When the files are loaded, an interpreter component of the Emacs program reads and parses the functions and variables, storing them in memory.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] They are then available to other editing functions, and to user commands.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Functions and variables can be freely modified and redefined without restarting the editor or reloading the config file.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In order to save time and memory space, much of the functionality of Emacs loads only when required.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Each set of optional features shipped with Emacs is implemented by a collection of Emacs code called a package or library.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] For example, there is a library for highlighting keywords in program source code, and a library for playing the game of Tetris.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Each library is implemented using one or more Emacs Lisp source files.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Libraries can define one or more *major modes* to activate and control their function.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs developers write certain functions in C.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] These are *primitives*, also termed *built-in functions* or *subrs*.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Although primitives can be called from Lisp code, they can only be modified by editing the C source files and recompiling.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In GNU Emacs, primitives are not available as external libraries; they are part of the Emacs executable.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In XEmacs, runtime loading of such primitives is possible, using the operating system's support for dynamic linking.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Functions may be written as primitives because they need access to external data and libraries not otherwise available from Emacs Lisp, or because they are called often enough that the comparative speed of C versus Emacs Lisp makes a worthwhile difference.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Bytecode still runs more slowly than primitives, but functions loaded as bytecode can be easily modified and re-loaded, and bytecode files are cross-platform software.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The standard Emacs Lisp code distributed with Emacs is loaded as bytecode, although the matching source files are usually provided for the user's reference as well.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] User-supplied extensions are typically not byte-compiled, as they are neither as large nor as computationally intensive.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The "cl-lib" package implements a fairly large subset of Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] This package replaces an earlier "cl" package, which would overwrite existing Emacs Lisp function definitions with ones more similar to those found in Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp (unlike some other Lisp implementations) does not do tail-call optimization.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Without this, tail recursions can eventually lead to stack overflow.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] The apel library aids in writing portable Emacs Lisp code, with the help of the polysylabi platform bridge.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Emacs Lisp is a Lisp-2 like Common Lisp, meaning that it has a function namespace which is separate from the namespace it uses for other variables.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Like MacLisp, Emacs Lisp uses dynamic scope, offering static (or lexical) as an option starting from version 24.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] It can be activated by setting the file local variable `lexical-binding`.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Before this option was added, one could use the `lexical-let` macro from the (now deprecated) "cl" package to provide effective lexical scope.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In dynamic scoping, if a programmer declares a variable within the scope of a function, it is available to subroutines called from within that function.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Originally, this was intended as an optimization; lexical scoping was still uncommon and of uncertain performance.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] In computer scientist Olin Shivers's recollection, "I asked RMS when he was implementing emacs lisp why it was dynamically scoped and his exact reply was that lexical scope was too inefficient." Dynamic scoping was also meant to provide greater flexibility for user customizations.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] However, dynamic scoping has several disadvantages.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Firstly, it can easily lead to bugs in large programs, due to unintended interactions between variables in different functions.
[src:emacs-lisp/emacs-lisp] Secondly, accessing variables under dynamic scoping is generally slower than under lexical scoping.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The program's tagline is "the extensible self-documenting text editor." Most functionality in GNU Emacs is implemented in user-accessible Emacs Lisp, allowing deep extensibility directly by users and through community-contributed packages.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Its built-in features include a file browser and editor (Dired), an advanced calculator (Calc), an email client and news reader (Gnus), a Language Server Protocol integration, and the productivity system Org-mode.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] A large community of users have contributed extensions such as the Git interface Magit, the Vim emulation layer Evil, several search frameworks, the window manager EXWM, and tools for working with a wide range of programming languages.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The original EMACS was written in 1976 by David A.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Steele Jr. as a set of macros for the TECO editor, and in 1984, Richard Stallman began work on GNU Emacs, to produce a free software replacement to the proprietary Gosling Emacs.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs was initially based on Gosling Emacs, but Stallman's replacement of its Mocklisp interpreter with a true Lisp interpreter required that nearly all of its code be rewritten.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] This became the first program released by the then-nascent GNU Project.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs is written in C and provides Emacs Lisp, also implemented in C, as an extension language.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Version 13, the first public release, was made on March 20, 1985.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The first widely distributed version of GNU Emacs was version 15.34, released later in 1985.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Early versions of GNU Emacs were numbered as "1.x.x," with the initial digit denoting the version of the C core.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The "1" was dropped after version 1.12 as it was thought that the major number would never change, and thus the major version skipped from "1" to "13".
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] A new third version number was added to represent changes made by user sites.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In the current numbering scheme, a number with two components signifies a release version, with development versions having three components.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs was later ported to the Unix operating system.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] It offered more features than Gosling Emacs, in particular a full-featured Lisp as its extension language, and soon replaced Gosling Emacs as the *de facto* Unix Emacs editor.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Markus Hess exploited a security flaw in GNU Emacs's email subsystem in his 1986 cracking spree, in which he gained superuser access to Unix computers.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Although users commonly submitted patches and Elisp code to the net.emacs newsgroup, participation in GNU Emacs development was relatively restricted until 1999, and was used as an example of the "Cathedral" development style in *The Cathedral and the Bazaar*.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The project has since adopted a public development mailing list and anonymous CVS access.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Development took place in a single CVS trunk until 2008, and today uses the Git DVCS.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Richard Stallman has remained the principal maintainer of GNU Emacs, but he has stepped back from the role at times.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Stefan Monnier and Chong Yidong oversaw maintenance from 2008.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] On September 21, 2015, Monnier announced that he would be stepping down as maintainer effective with the feature freeze of Emacs 25.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Longtime contributor John Wiegley was announced as the new maintainer on November 5, 2015.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Wiegley was joined by Eli Zaretskii in July, 2016, and Lars Ingebrigtsen in September, 2020.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Wiegley stepped down in 2018, and Ingebrigtsen concluded his term with the release of Emacs 29.1, leaving Zaretskii as lead maintainer.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Stefan Kangas was appointed as co-maintainer in 2023, and Andrea Corallo joined Zaretskii and Kangas in 2024.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The terms of the GNU General Public License (GPL) state that the Emacs source code, including both the C and Emacs Lisp components, are freely available for examination, modification, and redistribution.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Older versions of the GNU Emacs documentation appeared under an ad-hoc license that required the inclusion of certain text in any modified copy.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In the GNU Emacs user's manual, for example, this included instructions for obtaining GNU Emacs and Richard Stallman's essay *The GNU Manifesto*.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The XEmacs manuals, which were inherited from older GNU Emacs manuals when the fork occurred, have the same license.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Newer versions of the documentation use the GNU Free Documentation License with "invariant sections" that require the inclusion of the same documents and that the manuals proclaim themselves as *GNU Manuals*.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] This policy is in place so that the FSF can defend the software in court if its copyleft license is violated.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In 2011, it was noticed that GNU Emacs had been accidentally releasing some binaries without corresponding source code for two years, in opposition to the intended spirit of the GPL.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Richard Stallman described this incident as "a very bad mistake," which was promptly fixed.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The FSF did not sue any downstream redistributors who unknowingly violated the GPL by distributing these binaries.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In its normal editing mode, GNU Emacs behaves like common text editors by allowing the user to type text with the keyboard and move the editing point with arrow keys.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Escape key sequences or pressing the control key and/or the meta key, alt key or super keys in conjunction with a regular key produces modified keystrokes that invoke functions from the Emacs Lisp environment.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Commands such as `save-buffer` and `save-buffers-kill-emacs` combine multiple modified keystrokes.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Some GNU Emacs commands work by invoking external programs, such as ispell for spell-checking and the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) for program compilation.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs also supports "inferior processes," long-lived child processes that interact with the editor.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] This is used to implement shell-mode, running a Unix shell as inferior process, as well as read–eval–print loop (REPL) modes for various programming languages.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs' support for external processes makes it suitable for interactive programming along the lines of Interlisp or Smalltalk.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Users who prefer the widely used IBM Common User Access keyboard shortcut layout can use cua-mode, a package that originally was a third-party add-on but has been included in GNU Emacs since version 22.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs uses the "minibuffer," normally the bottommost line, to display messages and request information, functions that are often performed by dialog boxes in GUI editors.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The minibuffer holds information such as text to target in a search or the name of a file to read or save.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] When applicable, command-line completion is available using the tab and space keys.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs keeps text in data structures known as buffers.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Buffers may or may not be displayed onscreen, and all buffer features are accessible by both Emacs Lisp programs and the user interface.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The user can create new buffers and dismiss unwanted ones, and many buffers can exist at the same time, limited only by available memory.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs can be configured to save the list of open buffers on exit, and reopen this list when it is restarted.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Some buffers contain text loaded from text files, which the user can edit and save back to permanent storage.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] These buffers are said to be "visiting" files.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Buffers also serve to display other data, such as the output of Emacs commands, dired directory listings, documentation strings displayed by the "help" library and notification messages that in other editors would be displayed in a dialog box.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Some of these notifications are displayed briefly in the minibuffer, and GNU Emacs provides a *Messages* buffer that keeps a history of the most recent notifications of this type.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] When the minibuffer is used for output from Emacs, it is called the "echo area".
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Longer notifications are displayed in buffers of their own.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The maximum length of messages that will be displayed in the minibuffer is, of course, configurable.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Buffers can also serve as input and output areas for an external process such as a shell or REPL.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Buffers which Emacs creates on its own are typically named with asterisks on each end, to distinguish from user buffers.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The list of open buffers is itself displayed in this type of buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Most Emacs key sequences remain functional in any buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] For example, the standard Ctrl-s `isearch` function can be used to search filenames in dired buffers, and the file list can be saved to a text file just as any other buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Dired buffers can be switched to a writable mode, in which filenames and attributes can be edited textually; when the buffer is saved, the changes are written to the filesystem.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] This allows multiple files to be renamed using the search and replace features of Emacs.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] When so equipped, Emacs displays image files in buffers.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs can split the editing area into separate non-overlapping sections called "windows," a feature that has been available since 1975, predating the graphical user interface in common use.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In Emacs terminology, "windows" are similar to what other systems call "frames" or "panes" – a rectangular portion of the program's display that can be updated and interacted with independently.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Each Emacs window has a status bar called the "mode line" displayed by default at the bottom edge of the window.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs windows are available both in text-terminal and graphical modes and allow more than one buffer, or several parts of a buffer, to be displayed at once.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In addition, there is follow-mode, a minor mode that chains windows to display non-overlapping portions of a buffer.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Using follow-mode, a single file can be displayed in multiple side-by-side windows that update appropriately when scrolled.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In addition, Emacs supports "narrowing" a buffer to display only a portion of a file, with top/bottom of buffer navigation functionality and buffer size calculations reflecting only the selected range.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs windows are tiled and cannot appear "above" or "below" their companions.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs can launch multiple "frames", which are displayed as individual windows in a graphical environment.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] On a text terminal, multiple frames are displayed stacked filling the entire terminal, and can be switched using the standard Emacs commands.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs can display or edit a variety of different types of text and adapts its behavior by entering add-on modes called "major modes".
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] There are major modes for many different purposes including editing ordinary text files, the source code of many markup and programming languages, as well as displaying web pages, directory listings and other system info.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Each major mode involves an Emacs Lisp program that extends the editor to behave more conveniently for the specified type of text.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The use of "minor modes" enables further customization.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] A GNU Emacs editing buffer can use only one major mode at a time, but multiple minor modes can operate simultaneously.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] These may operate directly on documents, as in the way the major mode for the C programming language defines a separate minor mode for each of its popular indent styles, or they may alter the editing environment.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Examples of the latter include a mode that adds the ability to undo changes to the window configuration and one that performs on-the-fly syntax checking.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] There is also a minor mode that allows multiple major modes to be used in a single file, for convenience when editing a document in which multiple programming languages are embedded.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs supports the capability to use it as an interpreter for the Emacs Lisp language without displaying the text editor user interface.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In batch mode, user configuration is not loaded and the terminal interrupt characters C-c and C-z will have their usual effect of exiting the program or suspending execution instead of invoking Emacs keybindings.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs has command line options to specify either a file to load and execute, or an Emacs Lisp function may be passed in from the command line.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs will start up, execute the passed-in file or function, print the results, then exit.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The shebang line `#!/usr/bin/emacs --script` allows the creation of standalone scripts in Emacs Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The *GNU Emacs Manual*, written by Richard Stallman, is bundled with GNU Emacs and can be viewed with the built-in info browser.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Two additional manuals, the *Emacs Lisp Reference Manual* by Bil Lewis, Richard Stallman, and Dan Laliberte and *An Introduction to Programming in Emacs Lisp* by Robert Chassell, are included.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] All three manuals are also published in book form by the Free Software Foundation.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs has support for many alphabets, scripts, writing systems, and cultural conventions and provides spell-checking for many languages by calling external programs such as ispell.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Version 24 added support for bidirectional text and left-to-right and right-to-left writing direction for languages such as Arabic, Persian and Hebrew.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Many character encoding systems, including UTF-8, are supported.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs uses UTF-8 for its encoding as of version 23, while prior versions used their own encoding internally and performed conversion upon load and save.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The internal encoding used by XEmacs is similar to that of GNU Emacs but differs in details.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The GNU Emacs user interface originated in English and, with the exception of the beginners' tutorial, has not been translated into any other language.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] A subsystem called *Emacspeak* enables visually impaired and blind users to control the editor through audio feedback.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The behavior of GNU Emacs can be modified and extended almost without limit by incorporating Emacs Lisp programs that define new commands, new buffer modes, new keymaps, add command-line options, and so on.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Many extensions providing user-facing functionality define a major mode (either for a new file type or to build a non-text-editing user interface); others define only commands or minor modes, or provide functions that enhance another extension.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Since version 24 GNU Emacs includes a built-in package manager accessible with the `list-packages` command that allows users to search for and install packages.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Historically, packages were downloaded manually, often distributed through the Usenet newsgroup gnu.emacs.sources.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Now, packages can be retrieved from various ELPA (Emacs Lisp Package Archive) repositories, including one run by the GNU Project.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Over time many popular packages have been included in Emacs by default; for example version 21 began bundling Org-mode, Calc, TRAMP, and many others.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In its early history, GNU Emacs often ran noticeably slower than rival text editors because the loading and interpreting of its Lisp-based code incurs a performance overhead.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Modern computers are powerful enough to run GNU Emacs with ease, but versions prior to 19.29 (released in 1995) couldn't edit files larger than 8 MB.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The file size limit was raised in successive versions, and 32 bit versions after GNU Emacs 23.2 can edit files up to 512 MB in size.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Emacs compiled on a 64-bit machine can handle much larger buffers.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] While GNU Emacs is largely written in Emacs Lisp, it makes extensive use of natively compiled C code to improve performance.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In addition to its own C code, it uses external libraries such as libxml2 for parsing XML.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Packages installed by the user can load dynamic modules.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Since version 28.1, Emacs can natively compile Emacs Lisp files via `libgccjit`, as opposed to just byte compiling them, resulting in a significant boost in performance.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs runs on a wide variety of operating systems, including DOS, Windows, and most Unix-like operating systems, such as Linux, the various BSDs, Solaris, AIX, HP-UX and macOS.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Many Unix-like systems include Emacs by default.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] In 2023 an official port for Android was released.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Version 23.1 removed support for some platforms deemed obsolete.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs runs both on text terminals and in graphical user interface (GUI) environments.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] On Unix-like operating systems, GNU Emacs can use the X Window System to produce its GUI either directly using Athena widgets or by using a "widget toolkit" such as Motif, LessTif, or GTK+.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] GNU Emacs can also use the graphics systems native to macOS and Windows to provide menubars, toolbars, scrollbars and context menus conforming more closely to each platform's look and feel.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] The correct spelling is "GNU Emacs", not "GNU/Emacs", following the rules of English, in the construction "GNU Emacs" the word "GNU" modifies "Emacs." That is the right way to describe a program called Emacs which is a GNU package.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Lucid Emacs, based on an early version of GNU Emacs 19, was developed beginning in 1991 by Jamie Zawinski and others at Lucid Inc.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] One of the best-known forks in free software development occurred when the codebases of the two Emacs versions diverged and the separate development teams ceased efforts to merge them back into a single program.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] After Lucid filed for bankruptcy, Lucid Emacs was renamed XEmacs.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] XEmacs development has slowed, with the most recent stable version 21.4.22 released in January 2009, while GNU Emacs has implemented many formerly XEmacs-only features.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] This has led some users to proclaim XEmacs' obsolescence.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Changes in each Emacs release are listed in a NEWS file distributed with Emacs.
[src:emacs-lisp/gnu-emacs] Changes brought about by *downgrading* to the previous release are listed in an "Antinews" file, often with some snarky commentary on why this might be desirable.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was originally created as a practical mathematical notation for computer programs, influenced by (though not originally derived from) the notation of Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It quickly became a favored programming language for artificial intelligence (AI) research.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As one of the earliest programming languages, Lisp pioneered many ideas in computer science, including tree data structures, automatic storage management, dynamic typing, conditionals, higher-order functions, recursion, the self-hosting compiler, and the read–eval–print loop.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The name *LISP* derives from "List Processor".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Linked lists are one of Lisp's major data structures, and Lisp source code is made of lists.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp programs can manipulate source code as a data structure, giving rise to the macro systems that allow programmers to create new syntax or new domain-specific languages embedded in Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The interchangeability of code and data gives Lisp its instantly recognizable syntax.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] All program code is written as *s-expressions*, or parenthesized lists.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A function call or syntactic form is written as a list with the function or operator's name first, and the arguments following; for instance, a function `f` that takes three arguments would be called as `(f arg1 arg2 arg3)`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] John McCarthy began developing Lisp in 1958 while he was at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Due to these factors, he consulted on the design of the Fortran List Processing Language, which was implemented as a Fortran library.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, he was dissatisfied with it because it did not support recursion or a modern if-then-else statement (which was a new concept when Lisp was first introduced).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's original notation used bracketed "M-expressions" that would be translated into S-expressions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As an example, the M-expression `car[cons[A,B]]` is equivalent to the S-expression `(car (cons A B))`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Once Lisp was implemented, programmers rapidly chose to use S-expressions, and M-expressions were abandoned.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions surfaced again with short-lived attempts of MLisp by Horace Enea and CGOL by Vaughan Pratt.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer using punched cards.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Russell was working for McCarthy at the time and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp dialects still use `car` and `cdr` (/kɑːr/ and /ˈkʊdər/) for the operations that return the first item in a list and the rest of the list, respectively.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy published Lisp's design in a paper in *Communications of the ACM* on April 1, 1960, entitled "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] He showed that with a few simple operators and a notation for anonymous functions borrowed from Church, one can build a Turing-complete language for algorithms.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This compiler introduced the Lisp model of incremental compilation, in which compiled and interpreted functions can intermix freely.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The language used in Hart and Levin's memo is much closer to modern Lisp style than McCarthy's earlier code.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Garbage collection routines were developed by MIT graduate student Daniel Edwards, prior to 1962.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] During the 1980s and 1990s, a great effort was made to unify the work on new Lisp dialects (mostly successors to Maclisp such as ZetaLisp and NIL (New Implementation of Lisp)) into a single language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The new language, Common Lisp, was somewhat compatible with the dialects it replaced (the book *Common Lisp the Language* notes the compatibility of various constructs).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In 1994, ANSI published the Common Lisp standard, "ANSI X3.226-1994 Information Technology Programming Language Common Lisp".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Since its inception, Lisp was closely connected with the artificial intelligence research community, especially on PDP-10 systems.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was used as the implementation of the language Micro Planner, which was used in the famous AI system SHRDLU.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the 1970s, as AI research spawned commercial offshoots, the performance of existing Lisp systems became a growing issue, as programmers needed to be familiar with the performance ramifications of the various techniques and choices involved in the implementation of Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Over its sixty-year history, Lisp has spawned many variations on the core theme of an S-expression language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some of these variations have been standardized and implemented by different groups with different priorities (for example, both Common Lisp and Scheme have multiple implementations).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, in other cases a software project defines a Lisp without a standard and there is no clear distinction between the dialect and the implementation (for example, Clojure and Emacs Lisp fall into this category).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Differences between dialects (and/or implementations) may be quite visible—for instance, Common Lisp uses the keyword `defun` to name a function, but Scheme uses `define`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Within a dialect that is standardized conforming implementations support the same core language, but with different extensions and libraries.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This sometimes also creates quite visible changes from the base language - for instance, Guile (an implementation of Scheme) uses `define*` to create functions which can have default arguments and/or keyword arguments, neither of which are standardized.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] After having declined somewhat in the 1990s, Lisp has experienced a resurgence of interest after 2000.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Most new activity has been focused around implementations of Common Lisp, Scheme, Emacs Lisp, Clojure, and Racket, and includes development of new portable libraries and applications.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many new Lisp programmers were inspired by writers such as Paul Graham and Eric S.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Raymond to pursue a language others considered antiquated.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] New Lisp programmers often describe the language as an eye-opening experience and claim to be substantially more productive than in other languages.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This increase in awareness may be contrasted to the "AI winter" and Lisp's brief gain in the mid-1990s.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As of 2010, there were eleven actively maintained Common Lisp implementations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] *Common-lisp.net* is a hosting site for open source Common Lisp projects.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Quicklisp is a library manager for Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Fifty years of Lisp (1958–2008) was celebrated at LISP50@OOPSLA.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are regular local user meetings in Boston, Vancouver, and Hamburg.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Other events include the European Common Lisp Meeting, the European Lisp Symposium and an International Lisp Conference.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme community actively maintains over twenty implementations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Several significant new implementations (Chicken, Gambit, Gauche, Ikarus, Larceny, Ypsilon) have been developed in the 2000s (decade).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Revised5 Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme standard of Scheme was widely accepted in the Scheme community.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Scheme Requests for Implementation process has created a lot of quasi-standard libraries and extensions for Scheme.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] User communities of individual Scheme implementations continue to grow.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A new language standardization process was started in 2003 and led to the R6RS Scheme standard in 2007.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Academic use of Scheme for teaching computer science seems to have declined somewhat.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some universities are no longer using Scheme in their computer science introductory courses; MIT now uses Python instead of Scheme for its undergraduate computer science program and MITx massive open online course.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are several new dialects of Lisp: Arc, Hy, Nu, Liskell, and LFE (Lisp Flavored Erlang).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The parser for Julia is implemented in Femtolisp, a dialect of Scheme (Julia is inspired by Scheme, which in turn is a Lisp dialect).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp and Scheme represent two major streams of Lisp development.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These languages embody significantly different design choices.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The primary influences were Lisp Machine Lisp, Maclisp, NIL, S-1 Lisp, Spice Lisp, and Scheme.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It has many of the features of Lisp Machine Lisp (a large Lisp dialect used to program Lisp Machines), but was designed to be efficiently implementable on any personal computer or workstation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp is a general-purpose programming language and thus has a large language standard including many built-in data types, functions, macros and other language elements, and an object system (Common Lisp Object System).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp also borrowed certain features from Scheme such as lexical scoping and lexical closures.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp implementations are available for targeting different platforms such as the LLVM, the Java virtual machine, x86-64, PowerPC, Alpha, ARM, Motorola 68000, and MIPS, and operating systems such as Windows, macOS, Linux, Solaris, FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, Dragonfly BSD, and Heroku.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme is a statically scoped and properly tail-recursive dialect of the Lisp programming language invented by Guy L.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It was designed to have exceptionally clear and simple semantics and few different ways to form expressions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Designed about a decade earlier than Common Lisp, Scheme is a more minimalist design.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It has a much smaller set of standard features but with certain implementation features (such as tail-call optimization and full continuations) not specified in Common Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A wide variety of programming paradigms, including imperative, functional, and message passing styles, find convenient expression in Scheme.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme continues to evolve with a series of standards (Revisedn Report on the Algorithmic Language Scheme) and a series of Scheme Requests for Implementation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is a dialect of Lisp that targets mainly the Java virtual machine, and the Common Language Runtime (CLR), the Python VM, the Ruby VM YARV, and compiling to JavaScript.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is designed to be a pragmatic general-purpose language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure draws considerable influences from Haskell and places a very strong emphasis on immutability.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure provides access to Java frameworks and libraries, with optional type hints and type inference, so that calls to Java can avoid reflection and enable fast primitive operations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure is not designed to be backwards compatible with other Lisp dialects.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Further, Lisp dialects are used as scripting languages in many applications, with the best-known being Emacs Lisp in the Emacs editor, AutoLISP and later Visual Lisp in AutoCAD, Nyquist in Audacity, and Scheme in LilyPond.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The potential small size of a useful Scheme interpreter makes it particularly popular for embedded scripting.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Examples include SIOD and TinyScheme, both of which have been successfully embedded in the GIMP image processor under the generic name "Script-fu".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] LIBREP, a Lisp interpreter by John Harper originally based on the Emacs Lisp language, has been embedded in the Sawfish window manager.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has officially standardized dialects: R6RS Scheme, R7RS Scheme, IEEE Scheme, ANSI Common Lisp and ISO ISLISP.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp was the first language where the structure of program code is represented faithfully and directly in a standard data structure—a quality much later dubbed "homoiconicity".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, Lisp functions can be manipulated, altered or even created within a Lisp program without lower-level manipulations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is generally considered one of the main advantages of the language with regard to its expressive power, and makes the language suitable for syntactic macros and meta-circular evaluation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A conditional using an *if–then–else* syntax was invented by McCarthy for a chess program written in Fortran.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] He proposed its inclusion in ALGOL, but it was not made part of the Algol 58 specification.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For Lisp, McCarthy used the more general *cond*-structure.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Algol 60 took up *if–then–else* and popularized it.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp deeply influenced Alan Kay, the leader of the research team that developed Smalltalk at Xerox PARC; and in turn Lisp was influenced by Smalltalk, with later dialects adopting object-oriented programming features (inheritance classes, encapsulating instances, message passing, etc.) in the 1970s.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Flavors object system introduced the concept of multiple inheritance and the mixin.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Common Lisp Object System provides multiple inheritance, multimethods with multiple dispatch, and first-class generic functions, yielding a flexible and powerful form of dynamic dispatch.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many years later, Alan Kay suggested that as a result of the confluence of these features, only Smalltalk and Lisp could be regarded as properly conceived object-oriented programming systems.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp introduced the concept of automatic garbage collection, in which the system walks the heap looking for unused memory.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Progress in modern sophisticated garbage collection algorithms such as generational garbage collection was stimulated by its use in Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Largely because of its resource requirements with respect to early computing hardware (including early microprocessors), Lisp did not become as popular outside of the AI community as Fortran and the ALGOL-descended C language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of its suitability to complex and dynamic applications, Lisp enjoyed some resurgence of popular interest in the 2010s.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp is an expression oriented language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Unlike most other languages, no distinction is made between "expressions" and "statements"; all code and data are written as expressions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] When an expression is *evaluated*, it produces a value (possibly multiple values), which can then be embedded into other expressions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] McCarthy's 1958 paper introduced two types of syntax: *Symbolic expressions* (S-expressions, sexps), which mirror the internal representation of code and data; and *Meta expressions* (M-expressions), which express functions of S-expressions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] M-expressions never found favor, and almost all Lisps today use S-expressions to manipulate both code and data.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The use of parentheses is Lisp's most immediately obvious difference from other programming language families.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As a result, students have long given Lisp nicknames such as *Lost In Stupid Parentheses*, or *Lots of Irritating Superfluous Parentheses*.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the S-expression syntax is also responsible for much of Lisp's power: the syntax is simple and consistent, which facilitates manipulation by computer.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the syntax of Lisp is not limited to traditional parentheses notation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It can be extended to include alternative notations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, XMLisp is a Common Lisp extension that employs the metaobject protocol to integrate S-expressions with the Extensible Markup Language (XML).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The reliance on expressions gives the language great flexibility.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because Lisp functions are written as lists, they can be processed exactly like data.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This allows easy writing of programs which manipulate other programs (metaprogramming).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many Lisp dialects exploit this feature using macro systems, which enables extension of the language almost without limit.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is written with its elements separated by whitespace, and surrounded by parentheses.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, `(1 2 foo)` is a list whose elements are the three *atoms* `1`, `2`, and `foo`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These values are implicitly typed: they are respectively two integers and a Lisp-specific data type called a "symbol", and do not have to be declared as such.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The empty list `()` is also represented as the special atom `nil`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is the only entity in Lisp which is both an atom and a list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Expressions are written as lists, using prefix notation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The first element in the list is the name of a function, the name of a macro, a lambda expression or the name of a "special operator" (see below).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The remainder of the list are the arguments.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The "quote" before the `foo` in the preceding example is a "special operator" which returns its argument without evaluating it.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Any unquoted expressions are recursively evaluated before the enclosing expression is evaluated.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The third argument is a list; lists can be nested.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators are treated similarly.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The equivalent under infix notation would be "`1 + 2 + 3 + 4`".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp has no notion of operators as implemented in ALGOL-derived languages.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Arithmetic operators in Lisp are variadic functions (or *n-ary*), able to take any number of arguments.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] equivalent to `(setq x (+ x 1))`, returning the new value of `x`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] "Special operators" (sometimes called "special forms") provide Lisp's control structure.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the special operator `if` takes three arguments.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If the first argument is non-nil, it evaluates to the second argument; otherwise, it evaluates to the third argument.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Of course, this would be more useful if a non-trivial expression had been substituted in place of `nil`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp also provides logical operators **and**, **or** and **not**.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The **and** and **or** operators do short-circuit evaluation and will return their first nil and non-nil argument respectively.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Another special operator, `lambda`, is used to bind variables to values which are then evaluated within an expression.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This operator is also used to create functions: the arguments to `lambda` are a list of arguments, and the expression or expressions to which the function evaluates (the returned value is the value of the last expression that is evaluated).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] evaluates to a function that, when applied, takes one argument, binds it to `arg` and returns the number one greater than that argument.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lambda expressions are treated no differently from named functions; they are invoked the same way.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Here, we're doing a function application: we execute the anonymous function by passing to it the value 5.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Named functions are created by storing a lambda expression in a symbol using the defun macro.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `(defun f (a) b...)` defines a new function named `f` in the global environment.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] where `setf` is a macro used to set the value of the first argument `fdefinition 'f` to a new function object.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `fdefinition` is a global function definition for the function named `f`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `#'` is an abbreviation for `function` special operator, returning a function object.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the original **LISP** there were two fundamental data types: atoms and lists.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A list was a finite ordered sequence of elements, where each element is either an atom or a list, and an atom was a number or a symbol.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A symbol was essentially a unique named item, written as an alphanumeric string in source code, and used either as a variable name or as a data item in symbolic processing.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the list `(FOO (BAR 1) 2)` contains three elements: the symbol `FOO`, the list `(BAR 1)`, and the number 2.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The essential difference between atoms and lists was that atoms were immutable and unique.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Two atoms that appeared in different places in source code but were written in exactly the same way represented the same object, whereas each list was a separate object that could be altered independently of other lists and could be distinguished from other lists by comparison operators.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As more data types were introduced in later Lisp dialects, and programming styles evolved, the concept of an atom lost importance.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Many dialects still retained the predicate *atom* for legacy compatibility, defining it true for any object which is not a cons.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A Lisp list is implemented as a singly linked list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Each cell of this list is called a *cons* (in Scheme, a *pair*) and is composed of two pointers, called the *car* and *cdr*.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] These are respectively equivalent to the `data` and `next` fields discussed in the article *linked list*.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Of the many data structures that can be built out of cons cells, one of the most basic is called a *proper list*.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A proper list is either the special `nil` (empty list) symbol, or a cons in which the `car` points to a datum (which may be another cons structure, such as a list), and the `cdr` points to another proper list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If a given cons is taken to be the head of a linked list, then its car points to the first element of the list, and its cdr points to the rest of the list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the `car` and `cdr` functions are also called `first` and `rest` when referring to conses which are part of a linked list (rather than, say, a tree).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Thus, a Lisp list is not an atomic object, as an instance of a container class in C++ or Java would be.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A list is nothing more than an aggregate of linked conses.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A variable that refers to a given list is simply a pointer to the first cons in the list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Traversal of a list can be done by *cdring down* the list; that is, taking successive cdrs to visit each cons of the list; or by using any of several higher-order functions to map a function over a list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because conses and lists are so universal in Lisp systems, it is a common misconception that they are Lisp's only data structures.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In fact, all but the most simplistic Lisps have other data structures, such as vectors (arrays), hash tables, structures, and so forth.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Parenthesized S-expressions represent linked list structures.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] There are several ways to represent the same list as an S-expression.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A cons can be written in *dotted-pair notation* as `(a . b)`, where `a` is the car and `b` the cdr.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A longer proper list might be written `(a .
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is conventionally abbreviated as `(a b c d)` in *list notation*.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] An improper list may be written in a combination of the two – as `(a b c . d)` for the list of three conses whose last cdr is `d` (i.e., the list `(a .
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp provides many built-in procedures for accessing and controlling lists.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lists can be created directly with the `list` procedure, which takes any number of arguments, and returns the list of these arguments.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of the way that lists are constructed from cons pairs, the `cons` procedure can be used to add an element to the front of a list.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `cons` procedure is asymmetric in how it handles list arguments, because of how lists are constructed.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `append` procedure appends two (or more) lists to one another.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp lists, being simple linked lists, can share structure with one another.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] That is to say, two lists can have the same *tail*, or final sequence of conses.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] the lists `foo` and `bar` are `(a b c)` and `(x b c)` respectively.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, the tail `(b c)` is the same structure in both lists.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is not a copy; the cons cells pointing to `b` and `c` are in the same memory locations for both lists.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Sharing structure rather than copying can give a dramatic performance improvement.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, this technique can interact in undesired ways with functions that alter lists passed to them as arguments.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This changes `foo` to `(a b goose)`, but thereby also changes `bar` to `(x b goose)` – a possibly unexpected result.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This can be a source of bugs, and functions which alter their arguments are documented as *destructive* for this very reason.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Aficionados of functional programming avoid destructive functions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the Scheme dialect, which favors the functional style, the names of destructive functions are marked with a cautionary exclamation point, or "bang"—such as `set-car!` (read *set car bang*), which replaces the car of a cons.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In the Common Lisp dialect, destructive functions are commonplace; the equivalent of `set-car!` is named `rplaca` for "replace car".
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This function is rarely seen, however, as Common Lisp includes a special facility, `setf`, to make it easier to define and use destructive functions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A frequent style in Common Lisp is to write code functionally (without destructive calls) when prototyping, then to add destructive calls as an optimization where it is safe to do so.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp evaluates expressions which are entered by the user.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Symbols and lists evaluate to some other (usually, simpler) expression – for instance, a symbol evaluates to the value of the variable it names; `(+ 2 3)` evaluates to `5`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, most other forms evaluate to themselves: if entering `5` into Lisp, it returns `5`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Any expression can also be marked to prevent it from being evaluated (as is necessary for symbols and lists).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is the role of the `quote` special operator, or its abbreviation `'` (one quotation mark).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, usually if entering the symbol `foo`, it returns the value of the corresponding variable (or an error, if there is no such variable).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] To refer to the literal symbol, enter `(quote foo)` or, usually, `'foo`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme also support the *backquote* operator (termed *quasiquote* in Scheme), entered with the ` character (Backtick).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is almost the same as the plain quote, except it allows expressions to be evaluated and their values interpolated into a quoted list with the comma `,` *unquote* and comma-at `,@` *splice* operators.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If the variable `snue` has the value `(bar baz)` then `(foo ,snue) evaluates to `(foo (bar baz))`, while `(foo ,@snue) evaluates to `(foo bar baz)`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The backquote is most often used in defining macro expansions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Self-evaluating forms and quoted forms are Lisp's equivalent of literals.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It may be possible to modify the values of (mutable) literals in program code.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if a function returns a quoted form, and the code that calls the function modifies the form, this may alter the behavior of the function on subsequent invocations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Modifying a quoted form like this is generally considered bad style, and is defined by ANSI Common Lisp as erroneous (resulting in "undefined" behavior in compiled files, because the file-compiler can coalesce similar constants, put them in write-protected memory, etc.).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp's formalization of quotation has been noted by Douglas Hofstadter (in *Gödel, Escher, Bach*) and others as an example of the philosophical idea of self-reference.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp family splits over the use of dynamic or static (a.k.a. lexical) scope.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Clojure, Common Lisp and Scheme make use of static scoping by default, while newLISP, Picolisp and the embedded languages in Emacs and AutoCAD use dynamic scoping.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Since version 24.1, Emacs uses both dynamic and lexical scoping.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A fundamental distinction between Lisp and other languages is that in Lisp, the textual representation of a program is simply a human-readable description of the same internal data structures (linked lists, symbols, number, characters, etc.) as would be used by the underlying Lisp system.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp uses this to implement a very powerful macro system.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Like other macro languages such as the one defined by the C preprocessor (the macro preprocessor for the C, Objective-C and C++ programming languages), a macro returns code that can then be compiled.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, unlike C preprocessor macros, the macros are Lisp functions and so can exploit the full power of Lisp.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Further, because Lisp code has the same structure as lists, macros can be built with any of the list-processing functions in the language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In short, anything that Lisp can do to a data structure, Lisp macros can do to code.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In contrast, in most other languages, the parser's output is purely internal to the language implementation and cannot be manipulated by the programmer.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This feature makes it easy to develop *efficient* languages within languages.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For example, the Common Lisp Object System can be implemented cleanly as a language extension using macros.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This means that if an application needs a different inheritance mechanism, it can use a different object system.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is in stark contrast to most other languages; for example, Java does not support multiple inheritance and there is no reasonable way to add it.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In simplistic Lisp implementations, this list structure is directly interpreted to run the program; a function is literally a piece of list structure which is traversed by the interpreter in executing it.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, most substantial Lisp systems also include a compiler.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The compiler translates list structure into machine code or bytecode for execution.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This code can run as fast as code compiled in conventional languages such as C.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Macros expand before the compilation step, and thus offer some interesting options.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] If a program needs a precomputed table, then a macro might create the table at compile time, so the compiler need only output the table and need not call code to create the table at run time.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp implementations even have a mechanism, `eval-when`, that allows code to be present during compile time (when a macro would need it), but not present in the emitted module.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp languages are often used with an interactive command line, which may be combined with an integrated development environment (IDE).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The user types in expressions at the command line, or directs the IDE to transmit them to the Lisp system.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp *reads* the entered expressions, *evaluates* them, and *prints* the result.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For this reason, the Lisp command line is called a *read–eval–print loop* (REPL).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The basic operation of the REPL is as follows.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is a simplistic description which omits many elements of a real Lisp, such as quoting and macros.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `read` function accepts textual S-expressions as input, and parses them into an internal data structure.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For instance, if you type the text `(+ 1 2)` at the prompt, `read` translates this into a linked list with three elements: the symbol `+`, the number 1, and the number 2.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It so happens that this list is also a valid piece of Lisp code; that is, it can be evaluated.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This is because the car of the list names a function—the addition operation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A `foo` will be read as a single symbol.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] `123` will be read as the number one hundred and twenty-three.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The `eval` function evaluates the data, returning zero or more other Lisp data as a result.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Evaluation does not have to mean interpretation; some Lisp systems compile every expression to native machine code.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is simple, however, to describe evaluation as interpretation: To evaluate a list whose car names a function, `eval` first evaluates each of the arguments given in its cdr, then applies the function to the arguments.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In this case, the function is addition, and applying it to the argument list `(1 2)` yields the answer `3`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The symbol `foo` evaluates to the value of the symbol foo.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Data like the string "123" evaluates to the same string.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The list `(quote (1 2 3))` evaluates to the list (1 2 3).
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] It is the job of the `print` function to represent output to the user.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] For a simple result such as `3` this is trivial.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] An expression which evaluated to a piece of list structure would require that `print` traverse the list and print it out as an S-expression.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] To implement a Lisp REPL, it is necessary only to implement these three functions and an infinite-loop function.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] (Naturally, the implementation of `eval` will be complex, since it must also implement all special operators like `if` or `lambda`.) This done, a basic REPL is one line of code: `(loop (print (eval (read))))`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The Lisp REPL typically also provides input editing, an input history, error handling and an interface to the debugger.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In Common Lisp, arguments are evaluated in applicative order ('leftmost innermost'), while in Scheme order of arguments is undefined, leaving room for optimization by a compiler.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp originally had very few control structures, but many more were added during the language's evolution.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Programmers in the Scheme dialect often express loops using tail recursion.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme's commonality in academic computer science has led some students to believe that tail recursion is the only, or the most common, way to write iterations in Lisp, but this is incorrect.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] All oft-seen Lisp dialects have imperative-style iteration constructs, from Scheme's `do` loop to Common Lisp's complex `loop` expressions.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] By contrast, ANSI Common Lisp does not require the optimization commonly termed a tail call elimination.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Some Lisp control structures are *special operators*, equivalent to other languages' syntactic keywords.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Expressions using these operators have the same surface appearance as function calls, but differ in that the arguments are not necessarily evaluated—or, in the case of an iteration expression, may be evaluated more than once.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In contrast to most other major programming languages, Lisp allows implementing control structures using the language.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Several control structures are implemented as Lisp macros, and can even be macro-expanded by the programmer who wants to know how they work.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Both Common Lisp and Scheme have operators for non-local control flow.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The differences in these operators are some of the deepest differences between the two dialects.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Scheme supports *re-entrant continuations* using the `call/cc` procedure, which allows a program to save (and later restore) a particular place in execution.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Common Lisp does not support re-entrant continuations, but does support several ways of handling escape continuations.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Often, the same algorithm can be expressed in Lisp in either an imperative or a functional style.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] As noted above, Scheme tends to favor the functional style, using tail recursion and continuations to express control flow.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] However, imperative style is still quite possible.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] The style preferred by many Common Lisp programmers may seem more familiar to programmers used to structured languages such as C, while that preferred by Schemers more closely resembles pure-functional languages such as Haskell.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Because of Lisp's early heritage in list processing, it has a wide array of higher-order functions relating to iteration over sequences.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] In many cases where an explicit loop would be needed in other languages (like a `for` loop in C) in Lisp the same task can be accomplished with a higher-order function.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] A good example is a function which in Scheme is called `map` and in Common Lisp is called `mapcar`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] This applies the `+` function to each corresponding pair of list elements, yielding the result `(11 22 33 44 55)`.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Lisp syntax lends itself naturally to recursion.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Mathematical problems such as the enumeration of recursively defined sets are simple to express in this notation.
[src:emacs-lisp/lisp-programming-language] Genera, renamed Open Genera, by Symbolics; Medley, written in Interlisp, originally a family of graphical operating systems that ran on Xerox's later Star workstations; Mezzano; Interim; ChrysaLisp, by developers of Tao Systems' TAOS; and also the Guix System for GNU/Linux.
